In his speech at the Scottish Event Campus in Glasgow, Scotland, President Biden emphasized the urgency of taking action on climate change. He stated that the current decade will determine the outcome of the climate crisis and called for global cooperation and ambition to limit global warming to 1.5 degrees Celsius. The President highlighted the devastating impacts of climate change, such as wildfires, crop failures, and extreme weather events, and emphasized the need to view high energy prices as a call to action for clean energy solutions. He presented his Build Back Better framework, which includes historic investments in clean energy and aims to cut U.S. greenhouse gas emissions by over a gigaton by 2030. President Biden stressed the importance of creating jobs and economic opportunities through clean energy initiatives and highlighted the United States' commitment to meeting its climate targets. He announced the release of the U.S. long-term strategy, which aims for a net-zero emissions economy-wide by 2050, and pledged increased climate finance support for developing countries. The President also highlighted collaborative initiatives such as the Build Back Better World initiative, the Global Methane Pledge, and the Major Economies Forum on Energy and Climate. He emphasized the need for all nations to set ambitious targets and specific plans to address climate change and called for greater support for developing nations. President Biden concluded by urging action and emphasizing the importance of preserving the planet and improving quality of life for all.